rdially

V. Nabokov





TO: JAMES LAUGHLIN

ALS, 1 p.





8-VIII-42

West Wardsboro

C/o Prof. Karpovich

Vermont

Dear Laughlin,

I have seen Yarmolinsky's1 and his wife's translations of Pushkin: their work is conscientious, reasonably exact and careful but they lack my main desiderata: style and a rich vocabulary. Without a good deal of linguistic and poetical imagination it is useless tackling my stuff. I shall control the translation as to the precise meaning and nuance, but my English is